    "note": "Measured on a shared x86-64 Linux cloud container (karac built from kara main 6474a73), NOT the corpus's Apple M5 Pro. Canonical M5 numbers in the sibling results.json are left untouched. Absolute times/sizes/RSS NOT comparable across the two files; only within-file cross-language ratios are the signal, and THIS container run was noisier than usual (rust_ovf/go stddev elevated) so read ratios, not absolute ms. Seq lane (fastest first): rust 226.3ms < c 240ms < rust_ovf 283ms < kara 341ms < go 434ms. BOUNDS-CHECK GAP FIXED: kara B-2026-07-17-1 (fix 6474a73) \u2014 the per-iteration bounds check on the in-place `row[k]=row[k]+row[k-1]` descending update loop is now eliminated kara-side (compute_descending_skips proves k <= i-1 < row.len() from a length pin + the enclosing counter bound). A KARAC_BCE_DESC_SKIP=0 A/B pins the win: 1.29x -> 1.19x behind equal-safety Rust (rust_ovf). RESIDUAL GAP: kara is still ~1.18x behind rust_ovf, now from a DIFFERENT cause \u2014 B-2026-07-17-14 (open): the `while k >= 1` guard emits `dec; cmp $1; ja` where rust folds it into `dec; jne` (one extra dependent insn/iter). The overflow check (jo) is present in both kara and rust_ovf and is NOT the gap. All mirrors agree on the sink; correctness verified across interp/JIT/AOT/auto-par and valgrind-clean + ASAN-gated. Re-run bench.sh on the M5 to fold comparable numbers into the corpus tables."
